listing.name: Earl of East - Candle Making Workshops
listing.subtitle: Wax On, Wax Off

tip.text: Light it up at Earl of East's candle making workshops where you'll learn how to make a bougie flammable wax stick for you or someone you like a lot. Sniff out the perfect blend of fragrance and essential oils, then wax it all up, let it set overnight, and take it home the next day. You're literally conquering #hygge, you are an unstoppable lifestyle fairy.

Anyone yearning for yarn should shimmy on down to this weaving studio asap, where drop-in classes run the gamut of fabric-based creative outputs for all levels of expertise. Tapestry weaving, pompom earring making, embroidery and sashiko stitching are just some of the more obscure classes they run.

It's a relaxed, wholesome and fun environment where classes have been known to start with a shot of tequilla and BYOB is allowed. Come learn to weave your way to ultimate textile goals and prepare your relatives for an onslaught of woven gifts come Christmas time.

It might be a firm favourite of hen parties and young 'uns, but Wonderland Ceramics is a soothing place to while away a rainy afternoon. The cafe is, you might have guessed, inspired by Alice in Wonderland, with illustrations covering the walls and candles coming out of tea cups. Come in, choose some of the readymade plates, bowls or mugs and give them a thorough, good and proper, committed bit of painting. That'll set you back about £15, and you can collect the pieces a few days later.

They serve tea, coffee and a few snacks whilst you can also BYOB for a small corkage fee. And if you wanna try your hand at the wheel, pottery classes are also available.

Is there anything that doesn't exist within the boundaries of Lee Valley Park? To add to its already impressive arsenal of activities they've got an equestrian centre which is just great if you're in the mood to learn to ride. You're looking at an indoor arena and two floodlit riding arenas: 25 acres of prime horse riding land. There are plenty of different sessions, from group lessons to have-a-go lessons and private classes. Prices range from £30 (group lessons) to £70 (private tuition).

Ceramics sure has become popular in recent times - it makes us wish we'd invested in it rather than cryptocurrency. Turning Earth are regal princes of the trade and this is their second outpost - the light-filled top floor of an old hardware factory which encompasses some 8,500 square feet.

The centre includes a large open-plan membership studio where part-time professional makers, serious hobbyists and beginners work together in a community environment. The space also includes a classroom for ceramics courses for those new to the craft, where 12-week courses are taught by the pros. Demand is high and so is the price for these courses, but if you like ceramics then why the heck not.

The legends at Dalston Superstore must've heard our prayers, because they opened our dream venue: a late-night karaoke bar hosted by drag queens. Two words: Yas. Kween.

This is a Thursday-Saturday affair, and it gets raucous at prime times. It works like this: you book a table, show up with your least musically-talented friends (you can't risk anyone stealing your thunder), queue up your fave jam, and then perform to a captive audience of drag queens and drunkies. Late-night karaoke-ers (the venue is open till 2:00 on Thursday and 3:00 on Fridays and Saturdays) can just rock up without a booking, and spotlight-shy singers can hire a private room. They also offer 'party packages' with pies from Voodoo Rays upstairs and bubbly to get you in the belting mood.

Forget the corporate and generic chains in Central, this is how we'd like our karaoke served. What was once an 80s dive club is now an intimate bunker of karaoke, where 40 bods can squeeze in and lose all sense of time, space, pretensions and marbles. There's a bar serving the singing fuel, cordless mics and around 4000 songs available - not the widest selection but it does the job. You can also order pizza in here if you're looking to make a night of it.

It's only open on Friday and Saturday nights though private hire is available most nights of the week - and it costs around £65 for an hour, £125 for two etc, etc, so it's best to roll in with a crew.

London's great and all, but there's a distinct lack of cliffs dotted around. Climbing buildings just isn't the same. Mile End Climbing Wall sorts all that - they've got a huge range of different skill-level walls, and top instructors to get you zipping up and down sheer surfaces in no time.You can have a £20 taster session to see if it's for you, with special bouldering courses available too.

Ceramics sure has become popular in recent times - it makes us wish we'd invested in it rather than cryptocurrency. Turning Earth are regal princes of the trade and this is their Hoxton HQ - an arty, light-filled studio inside two glass-fronted railway arches. It's a great place to make a wonky pot, we've gotta say.

If you can work independently, you can become a member - though the waiting list here is almost inconceivably long. However, they also do 12-week-long weekday evening or weekend morning courses which you can get involved with if you react fast enough and are prepared to shell out the fairly substantial bucks for it.

It might not have the biggest walls about, but size isn't everything. Right? This centre, a former printers, is all about bouldering, and they've got blocs from the easy to the very difficult indeed. There are bouldering socials three times a week if you're looking to make some pals, and there's a very friendly, communal vibe here if that's the kind of thing you're into. It's £10 during peak times, £7.50 off-peak.

Want to see the UK's largest board game cafe? That's rhetorical of course, who wouldn't want to see that. Proceed Clockwise is a large, light and airy place for getting into some unnecessarily tense and competitive action with people you previously considered friends. 100 people can fit in here to tackle all the games you'd reasonably expect from the classic to the contemporary to the way-too-complicated-to-try-and-learn-on-a-tipsy-Friday-night.

Sharing boards and some simple pizzas provide the sustenance alongside coffee and craft beers, and the cost for sitting in is £5.

Hackney Wick's life drawing class is a nice way to let those creative juices flow into something tangible after work. They run two classes: one on Monday at People's Park Tavern; the other on Wednesday at Stour Space and the deal is simple. You draw models who are sometimes naked, sometimes not, for a short while.

It's open to all levels, BYOB and guidance is offered too - our one tip would be to not look at the work of the person next to you, because we're pretty sure professional artists go to these things to build up their confidence. And who can blame them?

The legacy of the Olympics in LDN is a contentious subject - but one thing nobody’s complaining about is the fact we, humble peasants, can stretch our limbs in the amazing, world-class facilities left behind. The VeloPark offers the opportunity to race around the velodrome like the lycra clad boys & gals of 2012 did so well. We can't guarantee an impassioned roaring crowd with Prince Harry and Sir Paul McCartney cheering you on but we can guarantee you'll be on THE FASTEST TRACK IN THE WORLD!

They put on a range of sessions here including fitness and skills specials but if you just want to get a taste, the one-off experience is £45 and lasts an hour, coming with all the basics you need to ride a fixed-wheel bike on that steep, quick-fire track.

The speedy evolution of Tottenham continues apace here with a bouldering and yoga studio set up in an old warehouse. Oh, you're not excited? How about if we tell you it's London's largest bouldering centre! That sure got your attention, eh?

Here you'll find hundreds of bouldering problems but also plenty of places to hang about and socialise in and talk about whatever is on your mind - we suggest bouldering related topics to avoid looking like a fraud. There's also a yoga studio, a fully equipped changing room and a nicely stocked café.

From all our travels, we've found that the surest way to inject a little adrenaline into that bloodstream of yours is jumping into a go kart and racing around the track, feeling all Lewis Hamilton (minus the tax avoidance). Revolution Karting have got something of a monopoly going on in London with tracks - both indoor and out - all over the place.

This one in Mile End is, by all (their) accounts, the fastest in central. It boasts a 750m winding floodlit track that you can reach 50mph speeds racing around. They have all manner of deals and offers here which are very confusing, but if you want to turn up and have a couple of races, it's between £25-30.

It might look like your run of the mill reservoir, but if you know the right time to go and the right things to wear, you might just swim in this reservoir. On Thursday evenings and Saturday and Sunday mornings they hold open water swimming sessions where a load of serious swimmers clad in wet suits do their thing. You need to do an induction here before taking part, so book on for that.

Also, you can also book on for introductory sailing lessons here if you want to get serious out on the water. The course duration is 2 days and the cost is a mean £165.

Say hello to the UK's highest free fall abseil at the Arcelormittal Orbit in the Legoland developments of Stratford. If you think this big red squiggly mess looks as funny as we do, imagine how you'll feel as you abseil 262 feet down it.

The exhilarating experience costs £85 per person, or upgrade to £130 per person to include GoPro footage of your descent and a souvenir ArcelorMittal Orbit T-shirt.

Channel your spidey senses at this massive climbing centre in Stokey. Literally housed in a castle (and Victorian former pumping station), this regal climber's utopia is spread over five levels and boasts 450 routes. If you want to ditch the ropes, there are also plenty of bouldering routes, including some outdoors. The Castle is very much a community affair - check out their volunteer-run garden, where they grow produce sold in their in-house cafe.

Enigma Quest, as the name suggests, is more of a quest than an escape room. The idea is to tackle all the clues and puzzles and hopefully complete the mission, but there's no lingering fear of never escaping into the light of day again. The deal is similar to the rest: 60 minutes, a test of logic and cunning, and the satisfaction of some tricky but wholesome fun.

These guys made it big with their Harry Potter themed game, School of Witchcraft and Wizardry in which the detail is really quite staggering. But there are also two other games: the (strangely low aspirational) Million Pound Heist; and Interstellar in which you search for a new habitat for humans across the universe. Teams are 3-5 people and it costs £24-30pp depending on how many of you do it. And know this - it is hard.

If you want your spa a touch more on the rugged side with vodka, spanking and ice baths, then head along to Banya No.1. The only one of its kind in London, this is an authentic Russian bath house where, instead of a conventional sauna, water is splashed onto a tonne of super hot iron, causing hot steam and all those bad toxins to sweat straight out.

The Parenie treatment is the thing to get here, which involves spells in the sauna; being aggressively spanked by some oak leaves and twigs to reduce muscle tension; dips in ice baths and cold showers; and some Russian grub. Kate Moss and Bieber have kicked it here and just think how good their skin looks! The three hour Parenie experience is around £60.
